passages.text: KOJAMo.HE 12m Price Target: 7.10 Price: 10.71 Downside: 33.7%

We update our estimates post- 1H25 results. Our 12m PT decreases by \(5\%\) to €7.1, partly due to slightly weaker growth assumptions as the company focuses on maximising occupancy vs. pricing. We maintain our Sell rating.

Excess market supply: Oversupply of rental apartments persists in Kojamo's main markets with rented dwellings in these areas growing by c. \(44\%\) since 2005 vs. c. \(32\%\) overall in Finland. Kojamo is mostly exposed to households with 1 or 2 customers (78.7% exposure), which have increased in numbers broadly consistently since 1985, unlike households with 3 or more customers.

Limited balance sheet flexibility: LTV ticked up by 30bps qoq to \(45.7\%\) as of end- 2Q25 with property valuations still down \(1\%\) at 1H25 vs. most REITs in our coverage seeing increases. Kojamo's coverage ratio has decreased for 8 consecutive quarters from 4.1x at end- 1H23 to 2.4x at end- 2Q25. Post 1H25, the company sold assets, reducing LTV to \(44.4\%\) , a step in the right direction, but this was dilutive. The company initiated a share buyback to protect the FFO trajectory, in our view maintaining some uncertainty on the 2025 dividend as a result and reducing the deleveraging impact.

Valuation: Kojamo's shares currently trade at a \(5.2\%\) FY26E earnings yield and \(41\%\) discount to FY25E NRV/sh vs. a sector average of \(33\%\) discount. Given the limited resilience of rents in the absence of regulation and in the context of the market oversupply, we see the earnings yield in particular as relatively demanding.

Stock outperformance YTD: On our forecasts, Kojamo has relatively low returns vs. its cost of capital and low EPS and NOPAT growth in the mid term compared to our coverage. Yet shares have outperformed our coverage by c. \(15.5\%\) over 12M; we see c. \(34\%\) potential downside to our PT vs. c. \(10\%\) average upside for our

In Kojamo's main areas of operations, the oversupply of rental apartments persists as illustrated by (i) the number of rented dwellings in these areas growing by \(c.44\%\) since 2005 vs. that in Finland overall growing at \(c.32\%\) and (ii) management highlighting in the 2Q25 earnings call that there is still oversupply in the market, especially in the capital areas. Additionally, Kojamo is mostly exposed to households with 1 or 2 customers (78.7% exposure), which have increased in numbers broadly consistently since 1985, unlike households with 3 or more customers, as illustrated below.

The financial occupancy rate for Kojamo increased by 80bps qoq from \(92.8\%\) at end- 1Q25 to \(93.6\%\) as end- 2Q25 but the like- for- like rental income growth remained negative at \(- 0.4\%\) in 2Q25. Management highlighted on its 2Q25 earnings call that the company had to make compromises on pricing to achieve occupancy improvements, which in our view may result in persistently weak Iff rent growth.

On the company's balance sheet, LTV ticked up by 30bps qoq from \(45.4\%\) as of end- 1Q25 to \(45.7\%\) as of end- 2Q25. Additionally, Kojamo's coverage ratio has decreased for eight consecutive quarters from 4.1x at end- 1H23 to 2.4x at end- 2Q25. Post 1H25, the company sold assets, reducing LTV down to \(44.4\%\) , a step in the right direction, but was dilutive. The company initiated a share buyback to protect the FFO trajectory, in our view maintaining some uncertainty on the 2025 dividend as a result and reducing the deleveraging impact.
The company's weighted average interest rate decreased by 10bps qoq from \(3.3\%\) as of end- 1Q25 to \(3.2\%\) as of end- 2Q25; c. \(84\%\) of its total debt expires by end- 2029.

Kojamo has outperformed our coverage YTD by c. \(9\%\) and the FTSE EPRA Nareit Dev. Europe Index by c. \(11\%\) despite screening on our estimates as having low returns vs. its cost of capital and low EPS and NOPAT growth in the mid term on a relative basis to the

other companies in our coverage. We believe the shares re-rated as investors expected a strong occupancy rebound. However, we believe the share price performance is overdone, and we see the current valuation at \(5.2\%\) 2026E earnings yield vs \(7.3\%\) average for our coverage as demanding, especially given the lack of resilience on the top line.

We update our estimates after 2Q25:

EPS/DPS: Our 2025- 29 EPS estimates change by \(- 1\%\) to \(+5\%\) as we adjust our vacancy and pricing estimates to reflect 1H25 developments and incorporate the recently announced recent share buyback. Consequently, our 2025- 29 DPS estimates also change by \(- 2\%\) to \(+4\%\) WACC: Our WACC is largely unchanged at \(5.66\%\) as we update our cost of debt assumptions. Our 12- month EVA@- based price target decreases by \(5\%\) to €7.1, implying c. \(34\%\) downside potential, largely due to our weaker pricing assumptions in the near term.

Below we highlight the key risks we see to our price target and investment thesis. If any or all of these risks were to materialize, we could consider a more positive stance on the shares.
Higher occupancy: Should the company be able to increase the level of occupancy in the portfolio more than we expect, this would imply improving Ifl rent growth and returns on the portfolio.

Stronger pricing power than we currently forecast: Should the company benefit from higher pricing power than we expect, effectively having better supply/demand dynamics, this would also be a further driver of Ifl rent growth and returns.

Higher disposals than we currently forecast: Should Kojamo be able to make disposals at a high discount to book value and reduce its leverage, this would have a positive impact on our cost of capital assumptions.

Stronger balance sheet: Given the company's short debt maturity and above- average levels of leverage, we believe any improvement in Kojamo's balance sheet would improve ICR and decrease its cost of capital.

Lower cost of debt than we currently forecast: Should interest rates be lower than we currently forecast, this would have a positive impact on cost of capital assumptions as well as our earnings estimates.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
